posts.name: Ryan
posts.cooked: We want to outsouce tubestock, where do teams usually get their tubes done?

posts.name: Billfred Leverette (he/him/not Bill)
posts.cooked:
A sense of scope would help here.  Are we talking about simple cuts to length, patterned holes, “I want custom one-off tubes I can shove my special-for-this-year spur gear reduction into” tubes?

We’re cutting things on a mounted bandsaw and relying on REV’s grid and MAXTube tubing, and it’s going to be a while before that’s the thing that holds us back.

Assuming you’re talking about prepunched 2x1 / 1x1, CTRE and WCP have pretty good pre-punched options (0.5" hole spacing) for a reasonable price (same product, different warehouses).

REV also has it (they call it “MAXTube”), but their stock has internal corner bracing + drilling guide lines -depending on what you’re doing, that might not be the best. Last year, we used REV tubes as our frame rail on our drivebase - we ended up having to replace them 2-3 times because the tube would split along the guide line. Their MAXTube patterning for their MAXSpline shaft can be useful for various mechanisms with MAXSpline and structure + weight savings if you need it.

If you’re talking about something more custom - as mentioned above, you should specify scope. A lot of teams can get manufacturing sponsorships from local shops, which can greatly help with cutting down machining costs (time + money) - that’s a pretty good route to go. If you aren’t able to get a sponsorship, you still might be able to pay for custom designs - but likely on the pricier side. You could also attempt to ask a local team with better machining capabilities if they could assist - and you buy the stock - though that may or may not pan out, seeing as we’re mid season right now.

posts.name: Ryan
posts.cooked: Oh sorry about that, for context our team is looking at more complex tubestock cuts with lots of patterning (bearing holes, lightening, etc). We would normally cut these out using our CNC machine but the fixture that holds our tubestock in place is currently having issues. We were wondering if teams had ever managed to outsource  cuts through something like SendCutSend or Fabworks (but neither have tubestock cutting).

posts.name: EricH
posts.cooked:
Yeah, that’s now more along the lines of “Machine Shop Make Parts” rather than “Laser This”. (SCS and Fabworks are primarily laser-cut shops, by the way.)

You might look at Xometry or Protolabs. I’m not sure either has an FRC discount, and turn times aren’t the greatest (unless you pay extra). Personally I’d look around for “machine shops in [area]” and try to pick up an in-kind sponsor.

posts.cooked: Be on the lookout next year. Fabworks has been teasing a tube cutting laser.

posts.name: Matthew K
posts.cooked: we have a manual mill for this, but if you have a drill press, there are small 2 axis vises for drill presses that can do somewhat decent cuts, although they have more backlash and are not as accurate as a mill. They could probably knock out your lightening pockets and maybe your bearing holes, depending on the required precision.

posts.name: Chris Herzog
posts.cooked:
Don’t mill on a drill press - they really are only good for drilling vertical holes.

They don’t have the typically have the bearings to handle the side loading but way more important than that, your typical Morse Taper arbor holding the chuck holder can’t handle side loads and likely will come loose scattering an angry, rapidly rotating cutter (plus some chucks are just held in with a variety of Jacob’s and other tapers).  I’ve got a buddy who realized how much of a bullet he dodged when trying to use a drill press for milling (“I just need to do this one thing…”) when the entire cutter and holder came loose and buried itself in the drywall behind the drill press.  I think his pants went straight into the outside trash bin and he realized how lucky he came out of that.

Mills have a taper holding their tool holders in as well but the drawbar keeps them pulled in tight so the taper doesn’t release.  Drill presses are fine without a drawbar because the drilling force is pushing the taper(s) holding the chuck into position along it’s rotating axis without any side load.  It’s when side loading happens that things can get weird - fast.

Interesting, I wasn’t aware of this. That makes a lot of sense. Still if you need to do lightening or other cosmetic pockets, you can drill holes close together then hacksaw the internals. Bearing holes you could maybe step up, but I think you’d have trouble with a fitting reamer at that diameter into a drill press
